ngredients for relaxed or energetic getaways. Not only are the grounds home to a number of resident koalas but there is also a saltwater pool, BBQ facilities and a volleyball pit. Kiddos are kept happy in the childrenâ€™s pool with its octopus slide, famed jumping pillow and colourful playground while parents kick back.\r\n\r\nCoupled-up Groupies who stay in the Standard Cabin will find themselves in for a cosy treat with an open plan living-kitchen area and private bathroom. Reverse cycle air conditioning and a colour TV with DVD player ensure that guests are comfortable no matter the weather, and the self-contained kitchen means they can cook up a storm during their stay. Families or groups of friends who stay in the Manor Villa enjoy the same features, plus a verandah with an outdoor setting where they can wile away the evening and catch up over food and drinks.\r\n\r\nPort Stephens\r\n\r\nThough it is home to famous sights like Australiaâ€™s largest shipwreck and the expansive sand dunes from the Mad Max movie, Port Stephens is still one of New South Walesâ€™ best kept secrets. The small coastal town boasts photo-worthy scenery thanks to its sandy landscape and pristine beaches, which offer many ideal vantage points for spotting migrating humpback whales during the winter and spring months. A family-friendly destination like no other, the Port Stephens region is awash with cute cafÃ©s, water and land-based activities and a dose of fresh seaside air.\r\n\r\nFamilies often find they are kept busy at the resortâ€™s on-site facilities but for those eager for even more experiences there are a bounty of opportunities within easy reach. The nearby sand dunes provide hours of fun, whether it is a hike, 4WD adventure or simply sliding down the sandy slopes. Just over the dunes lies famous One Mile Beach as well as Samurai Beach, so folks have their pick on where to take up residence before jumping in the waves.\r\n\r\nPlenty of water-based activities are on offer in the 